Contribution

  • green party success under economic prosperity vs.Â recession (Abou-Chadi and Kayser 2017; Gourley and Khamis 2023)
  • economic decline/hardship and (green) political attitudes (Kurer and Van Staalduinen 2022; Schaub 2021; Rudolph and Gomm 2024)
  • Question: What is the micro-level mechanism for green preferences?

Expectations

Following postmaterial theory (Inglehart 1971, 2008) and previous literature:

  • H1: The experience of downward economic mobility causes people to prioritize economic growth over climate protection.
  • H2: The experience of downward economic mobility causes a decreased preference for green parties.

Long-term analysis

Data & Design

  • panel data from Germany, GLES (2016-2023), N = 37,000
  • predictor: change in assessment of personal financial situation
  • outcomes:
    • trade-off between climate protection vs.Â economic growth
    • preference of the German Greens
  • estimation: association between downward experience (quasi-treatment) and outcomes

Exploiting an exogenous shock for causal identification

Data & Design I

  • abrupt consumer price increases after Russia's attack on Ukraine
  • assumption: prices hit low income households immediately, affluent households are more insulated
    • 2020 GLES extension, N = 11,600
    • treatment: up to 60% of median household income
    • control: above 150% of median household income
  • difference-in-differences design

Discussion

  • personal economic decline indeed leads to prioritization of economic growth over climate protection
  • accompanied by decreased preference for the Greens
  • implications:
    • policy making: buffer social impacts of green policies
    • electoral competition: Greens as niche
